"{\n    \"introduction\": \"The Whiskey Rebellion was a seminal event in the early United States, wherein frontier farmers violently protested an excise tax on whiskey, challenging federal authority. It highlighted the tensions between federal powers and local interests. The rebellion followed the Revolutionary War, as the new nation struggled with debt and governance, leading Congress to pass a tax on distilled spirits to bolster federal revenue, sparking discontent in rural communities.\",\n    \"name\": \"Whiskey Rebellion\",\n    \"description\": \"The Whiskey Rebellion tested the resilience of the new U.S. federal government, establishing its right to levy taxes and enforce laws directly on individuals.\",\n    \"dates\": [\"1791\", \"1794\"],\n    \"effects\": [\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Federal authority affirmed\", \n        \"score\": 10\n      }, \n      {\n        \"name\": \"Increased government credibility\", \n        \"score\": 8\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Growth of political parties\", \n        \"score\": 6\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Tax collection enforcement\", \n        \"score\": 7\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Westward expansion policies\", \n        \"score\": 4\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Fries's Rebellion\", \n        \"score\": 3\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Alien and Sedition Acts sentiment\", \n        \"score\": 2\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Jeffersonian political rise\", \n        \"score\": 5\n      }\n    ], \n    \"conclusion\": \"In quelling the Whiskey Rebellion, the federal government, under President Washington, demonstrated its power and willingness to enforce law, a defining moment in solidifying federal authority and influencing early American politics and policies.\",\n    \"people\": [\"George Washington\", \"Alexander Hamilton\", \"Thomas Jefferson\", \"John Neville\"],\n    \"places\": [\"Pennsylvania\", \"Pittsburgh\", \"Monongahela River Valley\",